## Unattended exhaustion recovery (usage-limit auto-resume)
When this loop runs unattended, a usage/rate-limit hit must not end the run —
it must pause and continue once the window resets.

- Runner: `scripts/auto_resume.sh` (Claude Code). It detects the limit message,
  parses the reset time (or falls back to the ~5h window + margin), sleeps, then
  relaunches a session that reads PROGRESS.md and continues. Cap: [MAX_RESUMES]
  reset cycles.
- Cowork (no headless): a scheduled task fires after the reset window and
  re-runs the session prompt above against PROGRESS.md.
- Contract that makes resume safe — the loop MUST, every session:
  1. Keep PROGRESS.md current enough that a cold session can resume from it alone.
  2. Print the exact done marker `[DONE_MARKER]` only when fully complete, so the
     runner knows to stop instead of relaunching.
  3. Never treat "out of tokens" as "done".

## Subagents & Permissions

The adversarial reviewer and the permissions file are standard outputs — every
loop setup should include them.

Each subagent runs in a **fresh, scoped context**. Together they replace the
human plan-approval and merge-approval gates so the loop runs unattended, and
no agent both produces work and judges it.

### Plan critic (`.claude/agents/plan-critic.md`) — model: [tier]
Runs **after the plan, before any code**. Returns unstated assumptions,
dismissed alternatives, edge cases, and a verdict (PROCEED / PROCEED WITH
CHANGES / RECONSIDER). This is the gate that lets the loop start work without a
human approving the plan, and the mechanism that forces all angles to be weighed.
Invoke at: [when — e.g. "before implementing any item scored ≥15/50" or "every item"]

### Adversarial reviewer (`.claude/agents/reviewer.md`) — model: [tier]
Runs in a fresh context **after implementation**, so it cannot defend code it
never saw being written. Looks for correctness problems — broken API calls,
missing error states, hardcoded values, security gaps, UX dead-ends — not
approach (that's the plan-critic) and not style. Output: numbered list, or
"LGTM — no issues found."
Invoke at: [when — e.g. "after each PROGRESS.md item" or "before any UI change merges"]

### Explorer (`.claude/agents/explorer.md`) — model: [tier, usually Fast]
Read-only scout. Answers one focused investigation question and returns a compact
`path:line` digest, protecting the driver's context on long runs. No edit/write.
Invoke at: [when — e.g. "any time locating code or tracing behavior would cost >2 file reads"]

### Verifier (`.claude/agents/verifier.md`) — model: [tier, usually Fast]
Runs the verification check and reports PASS or a triaged FAIL list. Never fixes —
that separation keeps the pass/fail signal honest.
Invoke at: [after each change, as the gate before review]

### Permissions (`.claude/settings.json`)
The `allow` list grants autonomous access to safe, reversible operations:
reading files, running verify scripts, grep, find, build commands.
The `deny` list hard-blocks destructive or irreversible operations regardless
of context: `rm`, `git push`, deploy commands, outbound network (`curl`, `wget`).

When the loop needs a new operation, add it to `allow` explicitly — don't
widen the allow-list preemptively. When unsure, default to `deny`.

